{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8cdf19fd-1afe-452c-83c3-de33f5f3c58e","content":"The standard approach is to **abstract the file system behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n1. **Define an interface** like `IFileSystem` with methods matching what you use (`WriteAllText`, `ReadAllText`, `DirectoryExists`).\n2. **Create a real implementation** that delegates to `System.IO.File` / `Directory`.\n3. **Inject `IFileSystem`** into classes that need file access.\n4. **In tests**, pass a mock/fake implementation.\n\nAlternatively, use the built-in `System.IO.Abstractions` NuGet package — it provides `IFileSystem` and a `MockFileSystem` out of the box, saving you from writing your own.\n\n```csharp\n// Option A: Roll your own\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n\n// Option B: Install the community package\n// dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions\n// dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers\n```\n\n**`System.IO.Abstractions`** is the most common choice in .NET projects — it wraps the entire `System.IO` surface and ships with `MockFileSystem` for unit tests.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"597c394c-9326-452a-8a71-7b7245dc45ff","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. This is a design/architecture question about testability, not a code change request. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":366,"requestId":"0BC0:1612ED:517BCB:5F0CC4:69F013AD"},"id":"fa65a7e1-315f-4c02-aebf-7fce4bd35f16","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:56:08.986Z","parentId":"f2b60fc4-4ec6-455d-b1c8-f708a9ca3be9"}
